        "symptom": "Heart murmur",
        "description": "An abnormal sound during the heartbeat cycle, indicating turbulent blood flow in the heart."
      },
      {
        "symptom": "Delayed growth and development",
        "description": "Children with single ventricle defects may experience slower growth and developmental milestones due to compromised circulation."
      }
    ],
    "treatments": "Treatment for single ventricle defects generally involves a staged surgical approach. The first surgery, usually performed within the first few months of life, is often the Norwood procedure. This surgery reconstructs the heart to improve blood flow. Subsequent surgeries, such as the Glenn procedure and the Fontan procedure, are performed as the child grows to ensure adequate oxygenation of the blood. Medical management may include the use of medications such as diuretics to reduce fluid buildup and ACE inhibitors to help the heart work more efficiently. Long-term care includes regular follow-up appointments with a pediatric cardiologist to monitor the child's heart function and development."
